~~~Krazaak posts~~~<br>
This probably isn't the best place to post this, but since I have nowhere else, it'll have to do. <br>
<br>
Alot has happened over the past few weeks and plenty of blame has been thrown around without any regard for people's feelings. Many comments have been strewn with emotion instead of fact. <br>
<br>
I thought long and hard before leaving Fam as well as since leaving Fam about what I thought the source of the problems were. Part of my decision in leaving was due to being unhappy, but not being able to explain why I was or how to fix it. <br>
<br>
I'm posting some of these insights because I think they might help somebody put things in perspective better and perhaps get people thinking about what can be done to make things better. There will be a few names in here, but the intent isn't to flame those people, because regardless of the outcome of their actions, I don't think they ever intended to harm the guild. <br>
<br>
[chop chop.... this was taking too long to type, gonna be brief instead] <br>
<br>
Hardcore players need to recognize that the guild relies on casual players as well and it is in their best interest to sometimes take a step back and hit some 'old content' to fill in gaps. <br>
<br>
Casual players need to recognize that the guild can not revolve around them. What you put into the game and what you get our are related and there are many advantages to being in Fam that don't drop during a raid. <br>
<br>
Officers aren't paid to be your whipping boys (girls). If you're unhappy with the game/guild then it's your issue. Officers may be able to help, but the responsibilty for resolving your unhappiness rests on you. <br>
<br>
Example: Vandic filled a great void in some ways by being the &quot;casual player's&quot; officer, but it just went too far. The mini raids for quests, epics and old-world mobs fills a great void that helps to give tangible rewards to casual players. Where it went bad though, is that just because somebody has a problem, doesn't mean the officers owe them a solution. Officers and the guild in general can only change so much for one person, without throwing the entire guild out of whack. By trying to solve everyone's problems, but not being able too, it created an increasing rift between players and officers. <br>
<br>
EQ is about having fun. If you're not having fun, then YOU'RE doing something wrong. You need to do what's fun for you, or you're going to burn out. <br>
<br>
Familjen's greatest weakness has been mobilization, because of that, we've lost races than we've won in the past and there's no better way to ruin everyone's night than to waste it training and getting trained by another guild while fighting over a spawn. A while after PoP came out, the officers saw a void in PoP, where raid level mobs basically sat waiting for somebody to come after them. We decided to jump at the opportunity to fill that void and accomplished a great deal in a relatively short time. Our hope was to gear up on tier 1-3 PoP loot and break into the elemental planes so that we could fill equipment gaps left from skipping a great deal of [highly contested] Luclin content. Somewhere, things broke down and some people complained we were going too fast and others that we were going too slow. <br>
<br>
Finally, on a more personal note, I've been surprised by the reactions of some people I considered friends. Since I've left Fam, it's been implied or stated that.... <br>
<br>
...that I wanted to see Fam fail without me. <br>
-- This couldn't be more wrong. I've been part of Fam for a long time, I have many friends in Fam and I'm offended that people I consider friends think that I'd find joy in my friends' grief. <br>
<br>
...that I just used Fam as a stepping stone so I could join HnE. <br>
-- This is bullshit. I didn't join Fam so I could get geared up to join HnE. I could have joined HnE when Isengard split into HnE if I was interested. I was in Fam because it was fun and I enjoyed it. I left Fam because I just wasn't enjoying the game anymore and when I sat down and thought about what in EQ was fun for me, I realized that I'd be having more fun in HnE. I don't hear people crying foul when somebody leaves another guild to join Fam, why take shots at friends when they move on? <br>
<br>
...that I went to HnE so I could coast and get loot that would rot. <br>
-- Gimme a break. Yeah, I'm happy when I get a neat piece of loot, just like I'm happy when I finish a quest or best a new boss. I only went to HnE because I knew I'd be contributing. They were actively seeking a replacement Shadow Knight and I thought it'd be fun to fill that role. Every piece of loot I get is earned with sweat and corpses, just like it was in Fam. <br>
<br>
...that I went to HnE because I didn't think Fam would ever break into the elemental planes. <br>
-- Also false. Frankly, I assumed Fam would probably be flagged for the elemental planes before I was, since HnE rarely visits tier 1-3 content. I expected most of my pre-elemental flags would come from HnE's and Fam's &quot;runes for flags&quot; agreement. <br>
<br>
...that I wanted to use Fam to get flags after leaving for HnE. <br>
-- Fam and HnE have an agreement in place that pays Fam for flagging their members instead of HnE competing with Fam for content. I had no intentions of being treated any differently than any other HnE member. <br>
<br>
So much for being brief... <br>
<br>
Anyway, I hope things work out. Fam's seen stormy times before and come out fine. The summer is always tough and having a newbie server out there can't be helping things.<br>
